The 58th Street Theatre as shown, occupies the site of a former 3 story stable and bears the numbers 206-202. The windowless structure appearing on the right occupies Numbers 214-208 and is in the rear of the American Fine Arts Building, #215 West 57th Street. (This set consists of a negative and a positive.)

Broadway, east side, north from W. 58th to 59th Street, showing a two-story taxpayer that is to be demolished. This site, an Ehret property is to be improved with two distinctive apartment houses. A full account is to be found in the Herald Tribune of January 21, 1940. View 2 is limited to this block front. Central Park West is at the left of the extensive preceding view. There upon appears the Mayflower (61st to 62nd Streets) and the twin-towered Century Apartments (62nd to 63rd Streets).

May 21, 1939
Views 1,2

P. L. Sperr

Broadway, south from Columbus Circle, showing at the left the 2-story taxpayer that is to be removed. This occupies the easterly frontage from Central Park South (59th Street) to W. 58th Street. The Herald-Tribune of January 21, 1940 carried a full account of the proposed apartment buildings that are to be erected here. Towering above same is the 20-story U. S. Rubber Co. Building, No. 1784 Broadway. To the right are the Arcade and Fisk Buildings. Separating these towering structures is W. 57th Street. Note the shadowy outline of the Empire State Building in the line of Broadway.

May 21, 1939
